A `Layer<ROut, E, RIn>` constructs `ROut` services given `RIn` services. `Layer.provide(inner, outer)` satisfies `inner.RIn` from `outer.ROut`, producing a new layer whose remaining `RIn` excludes what `outer` provided. `Effect.provide(program, layer)` then finally eliminates the R channel.

```typescript
import { Effect, Layer, Context } from "effect";

interface Config { readonly url: string }
const Config = Context.GenericTag<Config>("app/Config");

interface Db { readonly query: (s: string) => Effect.Effect<number> }
const Db = Context.GenericTag<Db>("app/Db");

const ConfigLive = Layer.succeed(Config, { url: "postgres://localhost" });

const DbLive = Layer.effect(
  Db,
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    const cfg = yield* Config;
    return { query: (_s) => Effect.succeed(cfg.url.length) };
  })
);

const Main = Layer.provide(DbLive, ConfigLive);

const program = Effect.gen(function* () {
  const db = yield* Db;
  return yield* db.query("select 1");
});

export const runnable = Effect.provide(program, Main);
```

